Question:
Convert a list of string numbers to integers and double each.

Input:
List<String> vals = Arrays.asList("2", "4", "8");

Solutions:-

Java 8 Streams convert string numbers to integers then double using mapToInt → map → Boxed. For input ["2", "4", "8"], produces [4, 8, 16].

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream strings → mapToInt(Integer::parseInt) → map(double) → boxed() → collect(toList()).

#Complete Implementation

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

public class StringToDoubledInt {
    public static List<Integer> convertAndDouble(List<String> vals) {
        return vals.stream()
                   .mapToInt(Integer::parseInt)
                   .map(n -> n * 2)
                   .boxed()
                   .collect(Collectors.toList());
    }
    
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> vals = Arrays.asList("2", "4", "8");
        List<Integer> result = convertAndDouble(vals);
        System.out.println(result);  // [4, 8, 16]
    }
}

#Thought Process
Primitive efficiency: mapToInt(Integer::parseInt) avoids boxing during parse.
Transform: map(n -> n * 2) doubles on primitive IntStream.
Back to objects: boxed() converts IntStream → Stream<Integer> for collection.
Single-pass: O(n) conversion + transformation.

#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty list: []
Non-numeric: NumberFormatException (e.g., "abc")
Null list: NPE on stream()
Null elements: parseInt(null) NPE
Zero: "0" → 0 → 0 ✓
Negatives: "-2" → -2 → -4 ✓
Overflow: Integer.parseInt range only
